n be derived by analyzing China’s workforce and labor relations side by side with the systems of other nations. The contributors to Chinese Workers in Comparative Perspective compare labor issues in China with those in the United States, Australia, Japan, India, Pakistan, Germany, Russia, Vietnam, and Taiwan. They also draw contrasts among different types of workplaces within China. The chapters address labor regimes and standards, describe efforts to reshape industrial relations to improve the circumstances of workers, and compare historical and structural developments in China and other industrial relations systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aCapitalism, sweat shops, Chinese labor, Global politics, Global economy, China trade union federation, Chinese industrial and labor relations, Chinese workforce.1 aBentley, Frederick Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButollo, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Anita, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChiu, Yu-bin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooney, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhara, Navjote, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing-chi Chan, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLin, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiu, Mingwei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLund-Thomsen, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat